  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provision of access to safe and quality education for conflict affected children in IDP settlements in NWS.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With the Syrian conflict entering its 10th year, the humanitarian situation in northwestern Syria continues to deteriorate, impacting all life aspects of the Syrian families. The outbreak of the Coronavirus epidemic have added yet another dimension to the crisis and increased the burden on the vulnerable families while they strive to acquire their most basic needs. The negative impact of the pandemic is amplified in areas of large gatherings such as camps, informal settlements, and schools where the ability to apply social distancing rules is severely limited and high level of vulnerability prevents households from investing in precautionary measures such as increasing the use of hygiene items/facilities and Personal Protection Equipment (PPE).

Therefore, PIN plans through the proposed project to cover up to 10 camps with a package of assistance that is aimed at responding to the education needs of said camps in a qualitative and safe manner. In brief, PIN proposes the provision of a blended online and physical education to 2,600 school-aged children in 10 IDP camps, to adequately respond to the COVID-19 created needs with a tailor-made approach. PIN will take on providing students and teachers with the essential teaching and learning materials as well as recreational materials. PIN will cover the learning centers operational costs, including COVID-19 prevention materials, and fuel for heating during the winter months in order to keep learning centers well-functioning and to create a safe and child-friendly environment. PSS will be a fundamental part of the project aiming to improve the well-being and learning capacity of children and teachers, who are not only traumatized by the war, but experiencing many new stress factors and serious impact of the virus. All these services will be provided through the blended approach that combines cautious physical attendance with the distance learning module that PIN has already established across its education portfolio, and allows a prompt shift between the methodologies when needed, adapting to the context.</narrative>
  </description>
